{"_id":"07f3d090-1a6d-11ed-813a-f794f19b085d","postId":"2017_03_aspnetcore-synchronization-context-ad62260e-a3f5-3648-b8e3-575b9b12f379","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2017/03/aspnetcore-synchronization-context.html","replyTo":"1e8d4130-1a6b-11ed-813a-f794f19b085d","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"On ASP.NET Core, `ConfigureAwait(true)` is the same as `ConfigureAwait(false)`.\r\n\r\n`HttpContext` is a property on the controller, so it doesn't need restoring. The old pre-Core ASP.NET had to restore `HttpContext.Current`, a static property on `HttpContext`; this property does not exist on ASP.NET Core.","date":"2022-08-12T18:31:50.719Z"}